        <body>
            <div type="article">
                <head type="article" tid="1">Dedication-aspiration</head>
                <div type="section" xml:id="EFT-KB-DEDICATION-ASPIRATION-KANGYUR-SECTION-article-1">
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="EFT-KB-DEDICATION-ASPIRATION-KANGYUR-SECTION-1"/>
                    <p tid="2">This group of texts is introduced in Situ Panchen’s catalogue to the Degé Kangyur as a fifth subsection of the Tantra Compendium, in addition to the subsections
                        containing tantric works of the four major categories, containing dedication prayers and expressions of auspiciousness as a concluding “branch of excellence” (<foreign xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">phun sum tshogs pa’i yan lag</foreign>). </p>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="EFT-KB-DEDICATION-ASPIRATION-KANGYUR-SECTION-2"/>
                    <p tid="3">The 19 works in the section are mainly short extracts from longer works. Toh 809-815 take the form of dedication prayers, while Toh 816-827 are mainly expressions of
                        well-wishing and auspiciousness in verse.</p>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="EFT-KB-DEDICATION-ASPIRATION-KANGYUR-SECTION-3"/>
                    <p tid="4">The catalogue only gives details of the first two texts, Toh 809 and 810, which are also the longest. The remaining works, it says, are present as final ornaments.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </body>
